Incident Report: Website Outage Due to DDoS Attack

Issue Summary

Duration: 2 hours 37 minutes (05/15/2024 10:23 AM EAT to 05/15/2024 01:00 PM EAT)
Impact: Our main website (example.com) was inaccessible to all users. This resulted in a complete loss of website traffic and potential revenue during the outage period. Approximately 100% of users were affected.
Root Cause: A Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack overwhelmed our servers, rendering them unable to respond to legitimate user requests.
Timeline

10:23 AM EAT: A sudden spike in traffic is detected by our monitoring systems, initially assumed to be a flash crowd or promotional activity.
10:35 AM EAT: As traffic continues to surge, website performance degrades noticeably. Initial investigation focuses on server resources and potential code bottlenecks.
10:45 AM EAT: Website becomes completely unresponsive. The incident is escalated to the senior DevOps engineer.
11:00 AM EAT: Further analysis of traffic patterns reveals the attack's signature, confirming it as a DDoS event.
11:30 AM EAT: Mitigation measures are implemented, including traffic scrubbing and rate limiting.
12:15 PM EAT: Attack intensity fluctuates but persists, requiring constant adjustment of mitigation strategies.
01:00 PM EAT: The DDoS attack subsides, and website functionality is gradually restored.
Root Cause and Resolution

The outage was caused by a large-scale DDoS attack originating from numerous distributed sources. The attackers flooded our network with a massive volume of malicious requests, exceeding our server's capacity to process them. This effectively shut down our website by denying access to legitimate users.

Resolution involved a combination of:

Traffic scrubbing: Filtering out malicious traffic at the network edge.
Rate limiting: Restricting the number of requests from individual sources.
Coordination with ISP: Collaborating with our Internet Service Provider to block attacking IP addresses upstream.
Corrective and Preventative Measures

To prevent similar incidents in the future, we will:

Enhance DDoS protection: Invest in more robust DDoS mitigation services and infrastructure.
Strengthen monitoring and alerting: Fine-tune monitoring thresholds for early detection of anomalies.
Develop incident response playbooks: Formalize procedures for handling DDoS attacks and other outages.
Conduct regular drills: Practice our incident response plans to ensure smooth execution in real-world scenarios.
Specific Tasks

Upgrade DDoS protection plan with our hosting provider by June 30, 2024.
Implement automated rate limiting rules based on traffic patterns by July 15, 2024.
Create a detailed incident response playbook by August 15, 2024.
Conduct a tabletop exercise simulating a DDoS attack by September 1, 2024.
Review and update monitoring thresholds for all critical systems by September 15, 2024.
